review_text:
Delicious, well balanced and produces a clean cup!

Brewed in a V60, 1:16 ratio (16g coffee, 255ml water) @ 3min total brew.
A well rounded espresso that plays well with milk drinks. Great in a cappuccino or latte. If you’re looking for a more classic flavour in your cold brew, this is a good choice, too!

Blew my mind as a V60. One of the better coffees I’ve had in a long time. Tons of green apple and citrus bursting out of the cup. A lingering chocolate and honey finish. Well rounded, bright and delicious.

Recipe: 

1:16.5 (16g coffee, 265ml water), 60g bloom for 45sec, 3:30min total brew time. Grinder at 15 using a Baratza Encore.

Very clean cup. A nice tea-like finish with a rounded front. Easy to drink and would definitely be a daily driver you won’t get tired of drinking.

Recipe:

Brewed in a v60, 1:17 (16g coffee, 272ml water), 60g bloom for 30 seconds with 3 minute total brew time.
Very interesting bag! The lemon came through strong in my chemex. Would buy a bag again in the future!

An amazing balance between fruity and chocolatey flavours. Great for when you’re not sure what you’re feeling more of!

V60 Brew Recipe:

16g : 255ml, 60ml bloom for 30 sec, 4 ~50ml pours, total brew time 3:30.

Grinder: Baratza Encore @ 15
Water temp: 90c

This blend really hits hard! Great as a double shot or in a cortado & flat white. The acidity and richer, nuttier flavours play so well together. One of the better blends I’ve had in a while! Ritual rarely disappoints 😬
Great as a batch brew or in the V60
Strong berry jam flavour. Some nice peanut notes. Nice with espresso. Tried with cold brew but I overextracted it. Will try again.
Great as a standard high quality espresso. Also delicious as cold brew.

When I first opened the bag, it smelled like a fresh bowl of strawberries. I had a little trouble getting my recipe dialed in for these beans, but it was with the trouble. Very very sweet, clean cup. As I expected from the fragrance, strawberry was the most pronounced tasting note (but was not at all overpowering).

This is my go-to blend to recommend to friends and family that are less interested in the craft aspect of coffee and more interested in a consistent and delicious cup. 
Nice, clean, balanced. Nothing to dislike!
Easy drinking.

There's a reason why this is a fan favourite - and it def doesn't disappoint one bit. Probably one of the best single origin I've personally had recently. And is definitely a must try and must buy in my books.
Super interesting Brazil. Has some of that classic Brazil undertones but fruit and bright sweetness shine through on the top end.
Lovely as a filter and espresso. Perfect example of what a natural can be
What a unique and impressive coffee from Brazil. Not a traditional Brazilian in any sense, this coffee is sweet and citrusy and very balanced. Kittel does it again!
Pacamara beans are always intriguing. Even to the sight you can tell this coffee is unique. Chocolate and molasses make for a full body and delicious cup.
A classic you can always depend on! Perfectly balanced.
A complex yet classic Ethiopia. Floral and fruity notes make this a perfect summertime coffee.
The Hartmann family never disappoints, and this new espresso offering is no exception.
Floral notes of tea and lavender round this cup out perfectly.
Costa Rican coffees always peak my interest, and this one doesn’t disappoint! Complex and balanced.
I haven’t had an exceptional coffee from Mexico, and this one basically falls in line. Pretty flat, a little roasty, not my favorite.
This coffee is outrageous. Bursting with fruity flavor and mouthfeel. It’s a journey!
A unique Ethiopian, and roasted to perfection. Fruit and florals!
A classic Kenyan. I look forward to this release each year!
I’ve never been very impressed by a pea berry, but this one is good. A unique varietal and a good cup!
Like a creamsicle. This Tanzanian is tremendous!

I anticipate this release every year. It’s not often I buy multiple bags of a single coffee, but I buy this every time I see it. An incredibly fruity cup, and I believe this year’s offering was the best yet!
A dependable classic!
A sweet and delicate cup! Simply delicious.
You can tell this coffee has been picked and processed with care. Terrific offering!
The longer ferment lends to a sweet and lingering finish. Terrific coffee!
Good weather and a good crop produced a terrific cup brewed either filter or espresso.
One of my favorite Canadian roasters does it again with this delicious Guji!
The concord grape is heavy on the nose and comes through nicely on the palette. Truly unique cup!
An excellent Costa Rican coffee: well balanced and sweet, with a tasteful amount of acidity. Reminiscent of biting into an orange. Notably, this coffee is made using the yellow honey process.
A truly unique and complex Ethiopian. My first from Kaito!
Just as described, rich, nutty, jammy, and perfect for an americano.
I look forward to San Sebastián every year - this year was no disappointment!
A fine blend that’s perfect for gifting around the holidays.
This coffee is truly wild - delicious in every way!
A classic washed Ethiopian with a nice tea like finish!
I’ve only had one Sumatra that has blown me away, and this one wasn’t it.
Interesting peaberry from El Salvador! I’m liking what I’m seeing from Firebat lately.
Onyx does it again with a classic natural Ethiopian. Simply terrific!
A staple and a classic. You can always depend on this when you see it in the hopper!
A safe and sweet Ethiopian. Hale comes through again!
Floral and bright but not too fragrant. A very nice example of a washed coffee

As the description says, last year's harvest was truly memorable. There was a balance of berries and creaminess, as well as a pleasant lasting mouthfeel.

This year, I'm tasting some lighter citrus notes, more like a washed process. The berries come in very late at the end. Overall, still well balanced.
Roasted a little too dark for my preference. No nuance to this blend.
Love this natural Ethiopian from a classic Canadian roaster!
I don’t usually drink Balzacs, but I was hopeful about this one. Unfortunately, it was the same over roasted profile I’ve come to expect.
A classic Kenya from a classic Canadian roaster. Delightful!
This coffee was exceptional. Whenever I see any variety of honey process, I try and grab a bag out of appreciation for the delicate process. This one didn’t disappoint!
An interesting edition of an annual favorite! Detour never disappoints!
The yellow honey process highlights the qualities of this coffee. Sweet and very balanced acidity.
A classic and dependable profile for espresso, stands well alone or in milk based drinks.
Basic blend here, nothing to write home about.
I had a hard time dialing this coffee in, but shout out to Anchored for offering a Mexican bean!
Really nice Peruvian espresso, great on its own or in a milk based drink.
This coffee is over roasted, without nuance, and basically burnt.
One of my favourite single origin espressos. I’m always excited to see it in the hopper!
Very tea-like body with a wonderful peach overtone and dry pomegranate finish.
Very good! Tried it at east coast coffee madness. Will buy again.
Had a pour over at east coast coffee madness. Very bright and fruity.
eccm pour over. Smooth honey flavour with nice peach notes. Very good. Will have again.
Eccm. Fudgy. Very good.
Eccm. Chocolatey finish. Pour over
Eccm pour over. Peachy.
Very juicy with a round mouthfeel. Nice citrus acidity with a lingering chocolate finish.
My favourite coffee of eccm. Pour over. Very fruity scent.
bursting with flavor. One of my go to's for a great latte
Hudson (and Montreal's) finest espresso for  latte perfection
A great espresso with milk or as a long black. Decent over ice
So freaking silky. In the best way possible. I’d rate it 6/5 stars if I could. A little less sweet than the natural version they released (duh), but still fruity and floral.

Visuel des grains:
Belle uniformité. Une torréfaction un peu plus "foncé" que ce à quoi je suis habitué. 

Arômes:
Belle présence de fruits (cerise noire, prune) avec une touche caramélisée qui laisse percevoir une torréfaction plus poussée. 

Saveurs:
C’est ici que tout se passe! Honnêtement ce café m’a tout simplement surpris. La cerise noire est en avant plan avec une belle acidité qui se rapproche de l’orange sanguine. Le corps est sirupeux et propose une finale sucrée qui m’a vraiment étonné, venant d’une torréfaction de ce type. Je dois avouer que ce Kenyen est hors-norme mais vraiment agréable. Une belle découverte!

Recette utilisée:
V60
Ratio: 1:15 (20g dry)
Eau: 300g third wave water @ 55ppm, 93°c
Mouture: Baratza encore #20
Routine: Tetsu Kasuya
Big and juicy with bright floral top notes that linger
Tons of stone fruit notes, and very tea like. Classic Ethiopian profile.

Arômes:
Un café super fruité avec des arômes de gelée de raisin et de baies rouge.

Saveurs:
Avec les bon paramètres j’ai réussi à avoir des notes de pâtisserie à la mûre-framboise. Un léger sucre brun qui se marie à merveille à la cerise noire. Le corps est moyen et offre une belle persistance dans sa finale. De plus en plus sucré en refroidissant avec une acidité bien balancé. 

Recette:
V60
Ratio 1:15, 20g dry
Mouture: Baratza encore #19
Eau: 300g third wave water @ 70ppm, 92°c
Routine: Tetsu Kasuya (premier pour 40g, deuxième 80g)

This is my personal favorite when it comes to espresso from 49th. It was made to cut through milk like a hot knife through butter.

It’s great in a cappuccino and offers a light acidity that plays well with the dark chocolate covered almond and Brazil nut base.
Great coffee. Smooth. Fruity. Great finish.
A nice, clean Kenyan coffee, with a nice brightness. Drank as a batch brew
It has notes of Peach, Bergamot, and Floral, which is a good combination. The Bergamot brings down the flavour of the peach, making it a very even flavour profile. Not too fruity, not too earthy
Delicious as a straight shot (I prefer it this way), or even cut with a bit of milk. Great brightness, with sweet, caramelized, spiced finish!
A nice filter coffee that starts bright, and develops with some rich fruit flavours
Made on the V60 by Greg! Started with some great strawberry notes that turned into peach as it cooled down.

A very nice burst of nutty and chocolate flavours on first sip! It rounds out beautifully with a coconut and orange zest finish. It lingers nicely on the front of your tongue.

Recipe:

Method: Chemex (natural filters)
Brew temp: 95c
Brew time: 4:30
Ratio: 1:17 (25g : 425ml)
Routine: 80g bloom for 45 seconds; 4 pours @ ~85ml each.

A great espresso which you can use to ease people into the world of brighter specialty coffees. The light cherry acidity to this blend adds a nice pop when consumed as a double shot. The more classic chocolate and caramel flavours will definitely make an impact, especially when put into a cortado. 👌

An amazing daily driver. We regularly consume this at work and it consistently delivers. Well balanced between chocolate & molasses and lemon & orange. If you tweak your shots a bit, you can pull out some caramel, too. Great straight or with some milk.
Amazing flavour and very popular in our cafe.
Our house filtered coffee.

Arômes:
Au nez ce café regorge de fruits rouge. La framboise et la fraise sont à l’honneur.

Saveurs:
C’est définitivement un café que je recommande pour les amateurs de Kenyen. L’acidité est présente (pamplemousse) sans être trop agressive pour laisser place à une confiture de baies rouge. Un café qui devient de plus en plus sucré en refroidissant. C’est un punch au fruit, version café. Attendez-vous à une finale qui persiste, au plus grand plaisir des papilles! 

Je suis un amateur de café du Kenya et celui-ci est dans mon top 5 assurément :)
This is one of those coffees where you don’t need to add a thing to it. Very fruity taste makes you want more.

This roast is pushed too dark for my palate. There is a nice raisin undertone, but it quickly fades and finishes to a smoky and bitter finish with a lingering 90% dark chocolate note. If you’re into dark roasts, this is probably up your alley! 😄

Recipe:

Brew method: V60
Brew ratio: 1:15 (25g : 375ml)
Brew temp: 95c
Brew time: 2:30
Routine: 60ml bloom for 30 seconds, three 125ml pours.

This coffee is very sweet, very well balanced, and has a slightly heavy mouthfeel similar to honey. It also has a very clean rhubarb taste, reminiscent of strawberry-rhubarb pies I had as a child. Absolutely would buy and enjoy again
Clean raspberry and vanilla notes, with a lighter and juicier body. Fairly sweet, slightly too sour acidity. Still delicious!
Sweet, slightly tart acidity, lots of juiciness. Dark chocolate note rounds out the taste at the back of the palate. Would be a great first cup of the day

I typically stick to 'safer' coffees rather than more adventurous ones, but for me this roast walks a perfect line between wild and predictable. I'm not a particular skilled brewer, but I find I can get good acidity and sweetness out of it while still having a consistent, good old cup of coffee.

Very juicy body with a lovely coconut & raisin overtone that finishes as grapefruit, hazelnut and chocolate. It leaves me with a faint honey in the lingering aftertaste.

Recipe:

Method: V60
Temp: 95c
Time: 4:00
Ratio: 1:16 (25g : 400ml)
Routine: 60ml bloom for 30 seconds, 3 equal pours.
Made using the Tetsu method to try to bring out all of the fruity notes. Smooth finish, with nice bright notes and raspberry/chocolate in the back.

One of my favourite coffees I’ve had recently! Nice rich sweetness with a light acidity. 

V60, Tetsu method
A good alternative to a darker, more traditional espresso roast! No burnt or rubber tastes commonly associated with “dark” coffees.

This coffee surprised me. I was expecting the subtleties to be removed with the darkness of the roast, but they were still able to shine through. Dark cherry and dark chocolate were the most prominent notes with a smoky and bitter linger at the end.

To pull out more of the acidity I tweaked my recipe so it would brew quicker than normal to account for the darker roast and it definitely paid off!

Recipe

Method: V60
Ratio: 1:16 (16g : 255ml)
Temp: 95c
Time: 2:30
Grind size: 17 Baratza Encore
Routine: 60ml bloom for 30 seconds, 2 pours of ~100ml.
Really big and really juicy. First sip tasted like grapefruit juice!

A very sweet coffee which is approachable enough for anyone who is interested in just taking a couple of toes out of their comfort zone. I like this coffee enough to reach for it fairly frequently whereas some of my other beans, although very good I like to switch between.
I have this one

Great floral notes with a black tea body. Nice stone fruit finish, somewhere between peach and apricot.

Came out nice as a v60 using Tetsu method, or as an Aeropress
Very interesting savory note to this, without being too vegetative. Espresso prep.

Definitely one of the most interesting and unique coffees I’ve ever had (and I don’t typically like decaf)! 

Comes out great as a straight espresso, in a milk-based drink, or even as a filter coffee. Very versatile!

Some nice floral notes, with sweet and snappy flavour reminiscent of apple juice!

What a well processed natural! The strawberry and fruity notes are well defined and not at all bordering on over fermentation / winey. I’m super impressed by this. It goes down so smooth as a straight double shot. It has a wonderfully present rosemary note that shifts into a currant and strawberry jam with a nice mild dark chocolate linger. I’m sure if I tweaked my extraction I could pull out more of the fruit. Absolutely wonderful cup!
Had as an espresso. Very fruity (berry jammy) at first but not too much. Jammy taste subsides quickly and left a chocolate taste as it cooled. I want to try it in a cold brew.
Big fruity natural, well-suited for espresso with plenty of sweetness though nothing new and exciting there.
Freaking amazing, holy f.

Tried this as a batch brew, it came out nice, with some good floral and fruity flavours. I would definitely try it again, maybe using a pour over method to try and bring out some more vibrant flavours. 

Overall it was solid!
A consistent espresso that tastes good in milk-based drinks. A bit darker than what I would like to drink straight up, but tastes just about the same every time.

Some really nice flavours with a good body. Some nice chocolate notes, kind of like chocolate covered blueberries! 

I had it as a batch brew.

Arômes:
Au nez ce café est remplis d’étages: baies rouge, fruits tropicaux, sucré avec une pointe d’acidité perceptible et classique des cafés du Kenya.

Saveurs:
Un café tout simplement équilibré à merveille. Cerise et orange sanguine sont pour moi les notes dominantes avec une belle acidité qui s’apparente à la framboise. C’est juteux et de plus en plus sucré (baies rouges) lorsque le café refroidit. Aucune présence d’amertume ni de "dryness". Sérieusement un café torréfié avec soins et pour un premier café du Kenya de la part de Kaito, chapeau !! 👌

Recette:
Kalita Wave 155/ Ratio 1:15/ 20g dry/ 300g third wave water @75ppm, 90°c/ Baratza encore 16 (medium)/ Tetsu Kasuya routine

Wow. Just wow. The aromas coming from this as the bloom was going had me salivating. It smelled like a freshly corked White Zinfandel Rosé. A beautiful medley of grape, pear and fresh berries with the slightest hint of chocolate in the aroma.

As for the flavour, the punches kept rolling. A wonderful combination of strawberry, raspberry and red grape give the thought of chomping on a red starburst. There’s a slight dryness to it that tickles the tongue and a roundness that really gives this coffee a chew. It ends with a sweet milk chocolate + grapefruit finish. Highly recommended!

Recipe

Method:        V60
Grind Size:    Baratza Encore @ 16
Brew time:    2:30
Ratio:            15g : 255ml (1:17)
Brew temp:  95c
Routine:        65ml bloom for 45 seconds, 2 ~100ml pours, 5 gentle counter-clockwise rotations using a bamboo stirring stick.

Kaito did not disappoint with their first Kenyan offering! Holly and Paul do their best to find coffees that’ll delight their customers and it really shows with this sweet, fruity and complex coffee.

In a filter brew the strawberry is very present and is drawn across your mouth. It starts in the front and stays lingering in the back. It has a slight sharpness to it that turns into a brown sugar sweetness as it fades on the back of your palate. A nice blackberry tone sneaks in somewhere during the transition.

As an espresso, this single origin hits hard! Everything gets compressed into a sharp, punchy, fruit bomb that borders on Tomato-y. The strawberry and brown sugar linger even longer when consumed as a straight espresso shot and feel a bit more like a dark chocolate and berry treat.

Well done Kaito, you’ve roasted something special!
Loved the strawberry notes and fruitiness from this coffee, but it felt a bit drier than I was hoping (this could have been because of my brewing). Overall a nice natural that has a lot of potential!
I tried this coffee in a V60 and personally found it was extremely chocolatey! Almost like drinking a hot chocolate instead of coffee. It had a really smooth finish too, no strong aftertaste.

I am currently using the Espresso profile of the La Esperanza. This pairs really well in milk (been using it for flat-white’s). Subtle sweetness, with nice nutty finish. This maracaturra varietal is a margogype hybrid and is the first time I’ve enjoyed a coffee of this type.
Made this in a V60. There was such an intense cherry aroma and flavour to this coffee, it was great!
Fruity and big yet still delicate. Not the most out there gesha I've had but still damn good
A fruit forward espresso with plenty of sweetness and body. Very nice.
Beautiful in a Corrado. Sweet raspberries finish semi-dry and floral. Could literally drink this all day
Easy drinking but with enough character to keep you on your toes.
Really solid as an espresso black or with milk. It's exactly what they say, a comfortable blend. Excellently executed
This coffee was so good I had to pull 2 shots back to back. When I paired it with milk the subtle taste of grape came through nicely, but on its own as a straight shot, this natural was explosive!
Way prefer as espresso to drip. The peachy body and light aroma come through way better.
This coffee is easily in my top 3 of 2018! With lively fruit notes this coffee is a fantastic example of a naturally processed Ethiopian.
Enjoyed it in a batch brew! Wonderfully acidic and ends with a nice chocolate note.

Had in an American press. Made 22g coffee to 355ml water. Pre infused for 1 minute for 2:30 total brew time. Ended up with a cup that is very chocolatey. 
Also did this as espresso. Espresso brought out the fruit notes much stronger. Im surprised how much the flavour changed between these two methods.
Not incredibly exciting but a nice Everyman coffee
Legit one of my favourite coffees I’ve ever had. Still thinking about it fondly over a year later.

A nice, classic blend that goes incredibly well with milk. Nothing that makes you get out of your chair and yell from the mountain tops, but a nice cup to wake up to in the morning when drank as a flat white.

If you’re looking for something chocolatey and clean, this blend is a safe bet.

Despite this being a filter profile, I’ve preferred it as an espresso! I ended up going with a pretty high ratio and found the coffee to still have a great vibrancy. Fruity and sweet with a honey like mouth feel.

Don’t get me wrong, It’s still good as a filter coffee! But I found it to lean more nut & chocolate when brewed in a pour over. The fruit wasn’t anywhere as present.

Espresso Recipe:
16g : 50ml (1:3.3) @ 40 seconds
This is the first time I’ve ever had coffee from Myanmar. And it most certainly will not be my last. This coffee is in my top 3 for 2018.
Pulling as espresso and it’s a grape juice bomb

One of the best gesha coffees I’ve ever had. Full of the big aromas you’d expect from this varietal and sweet honey and fruit dominate the cup. So pleasing and juicy. I’ll remember this one for awhile

Ana Sora is a yearly favourite a mine.  This 2018 crop was not as much of a fruit bomb as previous harvests.  Still very fruity and sweet, but lacking the intense strawberry jam flavour and aroma that were so distinct in previous years.  Still a very delicious coffee.

I remember last year’s harvest fondly so seeing this come back made me incredibly happy!

Not over fermented and has a wonderful balance of melon and chocolate when brewed in a Chemex.

It also extracts very nicely as an espresso. Though harder to dial in, it can give a wonderful berry compote flavour / mouthfeel with a lingering chocolate finish. In a flat white the jam cuts through the milk like a razor and offers almost a pie like flavour.

Brew Recipe:

Method: Chemex
Ratio: 16g : 280ml (1:17.5)
Temp: 95c
Time: 3:15
Grind Size: 16 on Baratza Encore
Steps: 60ml bloom for 35 seconds, 2 pours @ ~110ml each, 5 light clockwise stirs during draw down.
Tried in American press and espresso. I get more nutty notes from the espresso. Definitely prefer it as espresso. Would be really nice in a latte.
A solid decaf! Very nice notes of milk chocolate and a hint of cherry pie. Enjoyed as a cappuccino.
Very pleasing & floral aromatics welcome you as you brew this delicious coffee. Very clean finish and a burst of sweetness. Not as super-fruity as some naturals.

The Mokonisa is what you expect from a natural Ethiopian coffee. Intense fruit, with delicate floral notes, reminiscent of hibiscus. A standout coffee from an up-and-coming coffee roaster. Definitely worth picking up a bag.

Do you like Gesha? I bet you do! This Colombian Gesha is everything you like: lots of fruits layers, raspberry low-acidity, sweet and juicy melon taste with a winery taste that I like so much about Gesha coffee. Lingering finish with a hint of spice (still not sure which one tho). If you wanna treat yourself, go ahead !

Recipe:
Ratio 1:16,6/ 18g dry/ 300gThird wave water @ 150ppm, 94°c/  Comadante 22/ 4 pour every 45" (50•50•50•150)/ TBT 3'30"/ BWT 264g/ TDS 1.31/ EY 19.21%
Super bright and pleasantly sweet. I'm pretty shocked this is a washed Columbian but there is some of that floral/dry nut on the nose
Very bright. Definitely getting some grapefruit flavours in there.

I’ve been tasting many WASHED Ethiopia beans, and this is the first Natural process I’ve bought and taken home. Tried it as a Cortado at a coffee shop when I picked up a bag, and I really enjoyed it with the milk. Got home and brewed in the V60, and the flavors came alive, without being overpowering. Tastes of a mild tropical fruit, with hints of berry.
Sugar cane process helps this coffee retain a ton of flavour for a decaf.

I have loved this Colombian especially as an espresso. Worked really well for me for Americano’s. A very classic espresso, with great toffee notes (couldn’t use that as a tasting note as it’s not an option!) The story behind this coffee is even more incredible. Have a read up on it over at RoofTop’s website.
Well rounded. Nice all around coffee.
A little tough to dial this one in but when it's brewed really well it shines with sweet berry and clean floral notes.

Disclaimer - I had a different variety of sweet tooth than what is listed here - it’s a rotating blend. The one I had was organic hambela gotiti from Ethiopia. Grown by gottiti kebele producers. It was possibly the best espresso I’ve had. Floral and smooth in an Americano. I love it.

I’ve been enjoying this coffee as a flat white at Bread & Sons on Bank street for a long time now and can’t get enough of it. Baristas who know what they are doing, for sure!

Having said as much, noting accurate tasting notes are hard with lathered milk but the chocolate notes tend to linger in the mouth for a full bodied sip every time. 

I Highly recommend this coffee and the shop it is served in!
One of my all time favourite coffees! I love that Abdul Wahid Sherif's coffee farm helps preserve the disappearing ethiopian forest! And bonus that is so aromatic.
so creamy as espresso! tastes like an artisinal marmalade and dark chocolate.

This isn’t your typical honey processed Costa Rican! I was expecting to be hit with something a little more berry and floral but was met with something more on the chocolate and stone fruit side.

Seth seems to have pushed the development of this coffee just beyond what would be typically done to a coffee of this variety and processing method. I would’ve personally liked to see it a little on the lighter side to accent the acidity a bit more.

If you’re looking for something not too intense to start your day with or you prefer the more subtly floral cups, you won’t be disappointed with this!

Recipe:

Method: V60
Ratio: 15g : 255ml (1:17)
Total Time: 2:50
Temp: 95c
Grind: 15 on a Baratza Encore
Routine: 60ml bloom for 30 seconds, 2 ~100ml pours, 5 gentle clockwise rotations of the slurry during draw down.

Maybe it’s the weather of the region or maybe it’s the intricate drying process, but something about the production of this coffee has created a truly outstanding coffee. 

I haven’t brewed too many pour overs with this coffee yet because of how good it’s pulling as espresso. One of the best shots I’ve pulled recently, and I just can’t stop.
Delightfully sweet and nutty!

This coffee is thick! Pleasantly surprised by the body on this. A lot of honey up front with some maple syrup in the finish alongside a bit of grape acidity. A fairly short finish, but just enough to keep you satisfied between sips. Not what you’d expect from a Kenyan coffee but I’m definitely not complaining.

Recipe

Method: V60
Ratio: 15:270 (1:18)
Temp: 98c
Time: 3:15
Grind Size: 15 on Baratza Encore
Routine: 60ml first pour w/ light agitation, 100ml second pour with 5 quick stirs, 110ml pour with 5 stirs for final draw down.
What a clean natural! Kaito really hit a home run sourcing this lot. For their first natural Ethiopian they didn’t skimp. Playing the long game really paid off 👌.
A nice, clean Guatemalan coffee. A great way to start the day and not get hit over the head with crazy acidity. Just the right balance of acidity and chocolate.
Great espresso, rich and good boy with a slight prune taste
A great single origin espresso that succeeded in waking me up AND making my taste buds happy! Well done 👍

What a clean cup. Absolutely loving it brewed as a Chemex. A delicate acidity that reminds me of the lychee jelly cubes sometimes used in boba tea with a hint of blueberry and a tangerine finish. This coffee sticks around! There’s a nice green tea dryness and hint of nutmeg in the finish. Highly recommend this coffee.

Recipe

Method: Chemex
Ratio: 25g : 425ml (1:17)
Temp: 98c
Time: 4:00
Grind Size: 17 on Baratza Encore
Routine: 70ml bloom for 30 sec, 100ml pour, 100ml pour with light agitation, pour to final weight. 

With each pour let the slurry empty almost completely.

Solid filter roast that really shines as an espresso! I wasn’t blown away when I first brewed it as a filter coffee. The acidity was preset but muted and it was mostly overpowered by a 75% chocolate note. 

After reading other reviews I decided to try it as an espresso. What a difference! The strawberry comes through with a jammy texture that ends with a nice pomegranate dryness. There’s a slightly herby undertone and it finishes with a clean lingering milk chocolate. The acidity gets lost when made with milk so I’d recommend keeping this for doubles or americanos.
Very solid espresso. For me, it was a good coffee, with some floral notes that I expect from a Guatemalan coffee. It didn’t stand out with any wild flavours, but definitely did the job!

Wonderful juicy cup of coffee! A nice silky, milk chocolate linger that reminds me of a letting a bar of Hershey’s melt on your tongue. It’s floral forward with a clean stone fruit and citrus acidity but still very round in the mouth.

Enjoyed as a Chemex. Unfortunately, I don’t have the recipe used!

C’était ma première expérience avec le procédé de maceration carbonique et j’ai été vraiment surpris par le résultat. On s’approche des notes d’un Gesha avec le côté crème soda (bubblegum) et une belle finale qui s’apparente à un vin. Super bien balancé, sucré et une belle petite touche acide qui est délicate.
Je n’achète jamais le même café deux fois, mais ici j’y ai fait exception 😇

Loved the juicy fruity notes and the tonic/bitter feeling it left on my tongue. Made as a Kalita and v60, came out nice as both!

Definitely a great option for those who are looking to go caffeine-free! It maintains some of the great flavours of the coffee, without tasting like a decaf.

Comes out nice in the filter or as an espresso
Excellent tasting, lots of fruit flavour.
Bale? More like BALLING! Very enjoyable fruity cup from Kaito.
Very clean tea-like body with a nice jasmine finish.
Quite an enjoyable cup from Seth Taylor. Started off tasting like an iced tea but finished with a strong floral taste.

A nice mix of acidity and tea with a slightly more syrupy body. The tomato flavour was definitely bordering on strawberry, but I couldn’t get my mind away from it once tasted. As it cooled it got closer and closer but never crossed the threshold into straight strawberry.
Pretty classic South American profile on this one! Great if you want a heavier body with a clean milk chocolate profile.
I cupped this coffee along with nine other coffees and this was by far the best of the bunch. Incredibly fruity aroma and taste, low acidity, very light.

There’s a nice acidity in this coffee. It reminds me of an 80% dark chocolate bar with a peach and raspberry acidity. It doesn’t linger much and falls a little flat overall. The body is fairly light. If it was rounder it would be more up my alley.
Had as an espresso. Extremely fruity flavour - much more than I had expected. I would buy it again but would love to try as a pour over or cold brew
Much less fruity than the hambela washed but the fruit is still there. I feel it’s more of an espresso roast than the hambela but I don’t like it as much.
Good espresso - I got an odd aroma of maple which was nice and unexpected. Hard to find in Canada but I would buy it again.
Enjoyed as an espresso. Very bright with a lighter body. The acidity was well pronounced and I feel like it makes a decent single origin espresso if served as a double or americano.
Clean and classic with an almost fruity acidity. Just a good ol' cup.
Love the notes of strawberry
Very interesting flavours came out when I brewed it in my Kalita. I expected a bit more brightness from it, but overall enjoyed the cup! Solid coffee, and an interesting Guatemalan option

Amazing black tea like mouth feel with a wonderful orange zest and milk chocolate flavour. It reminds me so much of a Terry’s chocolate orange! There’s a sweet brown sugar and black tea linger.

Highly, highly recommend this washed Ethiopian. Thanks Roasters Pack for including it this month!

Recipe

Method: V60
Ratio: 1:17 (15g : 255ml)
Grind: 15 on Baratza Encore
Temp: 95c
Time: 2:45
Water: Third Wave Water Classic Profile
Bloom: 40ml for 40 seconds
Pours: 60ml drain until 1:15, 100ml drain until 1:45, 55ml remove dripper @ 2:45

For their first Kenyan, this one truly is a stunner. Fruity, perfectly balanced, and just the right amount of acidity. I’ve always appreciated a great Kenyan, and this one reminds me why. Well done, Kaito!

I expected more from this coffee, to be honest. It seems to be developed a little too far for me, tasting mostly like roast until it cools off. Once it cools, some cherry and grape cut through. I think a lighter roast would have favoured this coffee!
Just a tremendous Ethiopian from the crew at Hatch. Roasted to perfection for this profile, this one has a tea like mouthfeel with an intensely fruity flavour. Peach, nectarine, and mandarin orange.

My first pour over! I had this at la finca in Montreal and it was delicious. At first I tasted all apricots and as it cooled I got more peach and lastly blood orange. It was a great first pour over and id love to try it again.
Decent espresso. More traditional tasting than I expected.

Roasted a little on the darker side but the fruitiness still came through! Very round, juicy body with a milk chocolate and slightly roasted finish.

Method: Kinto Dripper
Ratio: 30.3g : 500m (1:16.5)
Grind: 15 on Baratza Encore
Time: 3:50
Temp: 95c
Water: Third Wave Water Classic Profile
Pours: 
• 90ml bloom—45 seconds
• pour 200ml to 1:00
• @ 1:30 pour 200ml (400ml total)
• @ 2:30 pour 100ml (500ml total)
• remove Dripper @ 3:50

I haven’t been a big fan of Guatemalan coffees the past couple of months; most being less acidic and more on the “classic” side of the spectrum with their fruitier notes over powered by their chocolate and earthy counter parts.

I was happy to discover this one in the December Roasters Pack! Still on the chocolate side, but the stone fruit and slight berry notes still came through.

The mouthfeel reminded me of fuzzy peach and blueberry skins and the acidity the predominantly peach. The linger had quite a bit of bakers chocolate.

Recipe

Ratio: 1:17.5 (16g : 280ml)
Grind size: 15 on Baratza Encore
Time: 4:25
Method: V60
Water: 95c (Barista Hustle recipe)
Routine: 4-6 method

• 4 x 56ml pours

What a juicy, layered cup of coffee. La Palma y El Tucan have produced another complex lot and Rosso gave it the care it deserved. At first I was admittedly disappointed in the cup—the price of the bag left me with high hopes. After a couple more brews and reflecting on the sheer number of notes dancing around in my palate, I realized my judgement was being swayed heavily by the price point and my own bias.

Looking at this objectively, this coffee is complex, juicy, clean and littered with notes that shift as you sip. When you take into account the price and the labour of love this coffee was, everything comes together to create a high priced coffee that’s worth splitting with friends and geeking out over. If you can afford it, it’s worth while.

Recipe

Time: 3:25
Routine: 4-6

• 71ml second pour

Super fruity and clean. Great on a Kalita or in am Aeropress. Sweetness is present but not overwhelming.

A solid Guatemalan offering. The roast level had me worried at the start, but there was still a very pleasant undertone of peach and coconut that really carried this coffee home. It’s a good way to start the day and ease into the more “funky” coffees out there. There’s definitely a strong burnt sugar and toasty flavour that steals the show, but the finish is a nice bitter dark chocolate with a tad of the peach fuzziness.

A beautiful Guji from Hatch. Tea like and clean with stone fruit and citrusy at times berry-like acidity.

Definitely a bit darker than I expected (and upon closer inspection of the beans rather inconsistent in the roast level). But honestly I still enjoyed it. Not something I'd grab again but provides a semi sweet and chocolatey cup with just enough fruit acidity to keep it interesting
A classic straight forward cup most of the time. Sweet and smooth. But sometimes the brew is just right and it's straight up butterscotch and I'm very much into it
Decided to try this Kenyan as an Espresso and I was delighted. Notes of smooth caramel & toffee with a delightfully subtle sweetness.

An incredible coffee with a surprising sweetness.

Aromas: Prune.
Cupping: Very sweet and fruity, bubble gum (hot). Prunes, watermelon, stone fruit (cool).

Aromas: Spices.
Cupping: Citrus fruit and spices (hot). Spicy and mineral, reminds me of darjeeling tea
Agrumes et epices (cool).

Aromas: Fruity.
Cupping: Chocolate, cherry, strawberry, basilic, spicy.

Aromas: Caramel, spices.
Cupping: Spices, ripe banana, smokey (hot), caramel, spices, smokey (cool).

A little dark roasted for my taste - unfortunately we only had the espresso roast available for cupping which is obviously not ideal.

Aromas: Cherry.
Cupping: Orange, smoke, caramel (hot). Apple, smoke (cool).
The Kayon Mtn region has been one that I have truly enjoyed. This coffee continues that trend. Definitely add this to your “must-drink” list for 2019!
Wow. Truly a fantastic espresso. It shines in milk but stands so well alone or as an americano. I grabbed it as the Holiday Espresso. But this is what it’s currently sold as.
One of my favourite coffees right now from the folks at Pop Coffee Works. Grab a bag. It’s good!
First bag I had of this coffee was an amazing berry bomb, second one was a bit under developed

This coffee embodies what I imagine a Kenyan coffee should taste like. A nice comfortable brightness, with a fruity mouthfeel.

I made it in the Kalita wave, and this kept a lot of the features I really enjoyed about this coffee

This was my first time trying a coffee from Peru, and I couldn’t be happier with the result. The coffee had a nice body, and a nice rich chocolatey taste to it. 

The coffee came out great in the v60, Chemex and Kalita wave. It’s already looking to be one of my favourites of the year!
I really loved this coffee
we served this with a ginger-apple- rhubarb crisp. such a coffee deserves to be shared! We found it juicy and vibrant, somewhat tea-like body.
Reminded me of Pu Er aged tea and citrus aftertastes, great coffee.

This coffee is a little too over developed for my palate. Though I’m still able to get some stone fruit and a bit of spicy dark chocolate (which is great), I feel like the predominant flavour for me is toasty.

If you’re looking for something to satisfy your craving for a classic profile with a twist, this is a great place to start. If you’re after something with a higher presence of fruit with your dark chocolate (like me!) it might be worth grabbing one of Propeller’s African offerings!

Very smooth, light body, with an non aggressive citrus acidity to it and sweet after notes.
Not a huge African coffee fan but this was a pleasant medium light bodied drink. The blueberry notes kept me sipping through the floral aromas. If you like more floral notes you'll love this.

This coffee was a delight to have at méchants pinsons in Montreal. It was very bright right from the start and had incredible notes of blueberry, with some nice florals to accompany it. It's acidity was present but this coffee's balance was surprising . A great coffee to have in the afternoon!
Beautiful combination of almond chocolate with a hint of red fruit acidity and citrus aromas. Great everyday flavours with single origin excitement.
Nice balanced coffee with notes of red apple at the start, continuing to nectarine and a creamy finish/mouthfeel. Yum!
A good coffee but roasted too dark for me
Brewed with a Hario V-60. Clean, smooth, medium body and sweet. This is a coffee I could thoroughly enjoy everyday.

Enjoyed as a cappuccino at The Brockton Haunt in Toronto. This blend cut through the milk in a very blended and satisfying way. Really bringing out a more black tea with milk kind of vibe that ended with milk chocolate and brown sugar.
This sample was roasted 12/12/18. For being well over a month old, not sealed or frozen, wow. Just goes to show that good coffee and good roasting matter more than anything.

I enjoyed this coffee, though a do feel it was a bit dark for my taste. Still produced a nice cup, but a lot of the more subtle notes were often lost or hard to develop through brewing. I did have a couple cups that were more fruit forward and complex, but it was often a little muddled.
Beautiful and bright but not harsh or overly acidic. It had some really delicate berry sweetness and tea like notes. Lime came through in a couple particularly nice brews.
This blend seems better than previous years. Brighter and more fruit forward while still providing a more classic and reliable cup
Love how complex and yet clean this coffee is. Juicy nectarine with a grapefruit acidity and slight bitterness. Finishes like honey in black tea.
Seemed a bit overdeveloped for my taste. A drying chocolate and nuttiness that verges on burnt sugar. Still some fruit and acidity but not very forward
This one is a little overdeveloped for me. It’s still salvageable, but lacks any nuance. I think this coffee had more potential than the roast allowed it.
I heard so many rave reviews of this Naturally processed Ethiopian I had to grab a bag. Truly a delightful coffee. Delicate, sweet, and fully of juicy berry.
Loved it! Had it in a latte and it was the best I had :)
It’s so good I can’t stop drinking it and it’s ruined me for other coffee. I should drink less coffee but I’m powerless with this blend,
Like riding your favourite powder board on a bottomless day.
Good Lord! So good just tap it into my IV already.
What a wonderful Gesha! Delicate yet complex with sweetness and fruit-forward notes that delight the palate. I loved every single cup I brewed with this.

This coffee is special. From the packaging and presentation to the coffee itself, Augie’s nailed it. This bean has so much to say, I backed off on my 1:16 ratio to let it speak. Brewing closer to 1:17 the coffee opens up and the fruits come forward. Almost like a mulled wine, each cup only gets better with time as it develops.

This is a great all-day sipper. Clean and light bodied without too much acidity. Great for when you’re having a calm & relaxing day shielding yourself from the cold.

Nice notes of cherry that transition to a long maple syrup finish.

Loving the complexities of this! Such a great way to start the day. Juicy body, mild acidity but still present and a solid sugary finish.

I could really spend the day drinking this without any problems.

Delicious!
Well balanced but still comes in swinging with a pinch of acidity! Ana Sora always produces quality, year after year and Traffic definitely did them justice.
Impressive decaf. Well done!
Creamy and well balanced.
This coffee was a true palate pleaser. Very delicate, and tea-like with subtle notes of stone fruit and and pleasing sweetness.

Who doesn’t love Kenyan coffee? This one is a must. It delivers well on the promised notes and I found as well a hint of honey and a sweetness as it cooled. Brew this up and share it with your fiends!
One of the most silky and smooth cups I've had in a while. Tastes like chocolate covered almonds and vanilla cream

Had this on espresso at Structure's cafe on a very nice Sunday afternoon in February. As I admired the decor, I sipped away slowly at my drink. Roasters' notes such as peach and Honey were immediately detectable, although it wasn't a particularly sweet one. The highlight of this coffee was definitely it's vivid stonefruit-like acidity. If anything, it wasn't a very bright cup, but I only realized this after thinking about it for a while. If you're in for a nice post-meal espresso, this is a sure bet.
Thanks to Sean for serving up a great cup of coffee, I'll be back!
A nicely rounded dark roast coffee with nice sweet and toasty sensation that’ll leave your taste buds wanting some more.
Super sweet with a nice crisp apple acidity, this is the coffee that introduced me to my love of Guatemalan origin beans
Great coffee very fruity for a colombian.
Great blend! Full of flavours and amazing smooth finish!
Fresh fruit and nicely herbal. Almost had this cooling menthol effect. Spearmint like. Lightly sweet with a silky full body.

Really well balanced and brewed by the Escape team @ Croissant Croissant. Pushed higher at 1:17 in a Chemex the florality and tea like qualities really came through. There’s a hint of grapefruit acidity that sneaks in.

Enjoyed it in a latte at Croissant Croissant in Montreal. The blend managed to come through strong enough, even in a larger amount of milk. The chocolate and nut flavours were dominant with a bit of nutmeg on the finish.

Had this during the Croissant Croissant event. Enjoyed it as a single origin espresso. Had a nice punch with the date and like acidity. Started to change into a nuttier dryness during the finish.

Purchased a bag and brewed it as a pour over. The lime and date really shined with a nice burnt sugar / marshmallow under tone. The finish was still nice and nutty. A solid all around Colombian.

🥐🥐 approuve 👌👍
Beautiful balance of florals and fruit, smooth mouthfeel.
Delicate sweetness, enticing savoury note.
Great espresso! Wonderfully herb and black tea notes with a pleasant undertone of acidity. Nice round body.

Dang, Seth has done it again. The roast development really allows this Ethiopian to shine and all of its nuance to come through. A tea like body with classic fruit and floral notes. Tastes like fuzzy peaches.
I’m always thrilled to get my hands on an anaerobic process, and this one doesn’t disappoint. A classic Costa Rican flavour profile, but the body feels like a glass of whole milk. Outstanding.
This is an exceptional Colombian, boasting a unique level of acidity. Some real nice fruity qualities to compliment the full body.
Very light and sweet. Made in both a MoccaMaster as a batch brew and in a Chemex. Was really tasty hot, but also as it cooled! Would definitely try this in a cold brew.
Great coffee for beginners, a smooth and not too bitter flavour

I brewed this in my Kalita wave 185 at 24g:360ml. It came out with some delicious, deep chocolate notes, and finished off with dried fruit. This coffee was very soothing, and I’d definitely recommend it as a morning cup (it wasn’t too wild, so it’s the perfect start to the day)

I cupped this coffee (and then had it as a batch brew), and got some great stone fruit notes from it. It had a black tea-like body, but it did not feel too heavy. As a batch brew, the peachy/nectarine flavours shone through. Overall a nice coffee!

I found the best results for this espresso we’re when used in milk-based drinks. Sweet black-cherry notes present first and floral aromatics with a delicate sweetness as the coffee cools. Really glad I grabbed this.

Enjoyed this quite a lot as a cold brew! When the concentrate is diluted properly, it has a wonderful milky body with a nice, light fruitiness. It’s very clean for a natural and could easily be dipped on all day.

I’ve tried it as an espresso as well. Still decent as a single origin double shot but the development comes out more when prepared as a double shot. When layered with milk in a flat white you’re left with a pleasant fruitiness.
I love the berry-ness to this coffee. It has a great flavor. Very clean and not overpowering. Great in an Aeropress!
A truly remarkable Gesha coffee. Brilliant floral notes from beginning to end. Gets sweeter as it cools to leave very noticeable berry notes.

Awesome as a single origin espresso/americano. A nice berry acidity and sweet hazelnut finish that borders on Nutella.

I was disappointed in it as a filter brew. I found it lacked the depth I got from it in espresso.
So far my fave from these Roasters
Had as a pour over at la finca. Really nice chocolate with a bit of a fruit finish.

A nice, classic profile with a hint of acidity. A great way to start the morning. Well developed and loaded with dark/bittersweet chocolate. Would pair amazingly well with a nice, hearty brunch.

Enjoyed it in an Americano.

16g in, 40ml out @ 35s on Breville Barista Express.
Grind set to 7 on the outer wheel and 5 on the inner wheel.

A very nice and subtly sweet coffee. Perfect as the first cup of the day.

Kalita wave 24g:360ml

This one was a serious knock out of the park! Some good typical natural notes, but with a bit more acidity and a lighter body than usual. The cup was very clean, and didn’t have an alcoholic feel to it

Brewed as a V60, AeroPress and Kalita wave
Nice espresso with some good roasty and rich notes

This coffee definitely came out better as an espresso. I was getting some nice sweet, nutty chocolate notes, and a low acidity.

Espresso pulled at L’or En Grain, in Montreal, Canada

Very nice as a pourover! I love how light and sweet this coffee is! The body isn’t too heavy, and the coffee has a nice acidity

Brewed using Kalita Wave 185
Awesome as a single origin espresso in an americano. Love the body and the fruitiness with a chocolate finish!
A really nice, well balanced Guatemalan here from Kaito. Brews nice on either a V60 or Kalita Wave, and is perfect for the morning or evening.
This is a really nice natural from Ethiopia. Intense fruit hits up front but immediately lingers into a light bodied, tea-like finish.

I was excited to try this natural microlot from De Mello, but it didn’t quite meet my expectations. I think it’s roasted fine, but it tastes over fermented. I like naturals, but I can’t seem to figure out what the coffee itself is trying to say here. All I can taste is the process.

A nice syrupy, juicy body paired with the tartness of an apple and the flavours of peach & lime that finish in a fresh basil & brown sugar linger.

This coffee is an absolute winner in my books. I really hope to see more roasters sourcing from China. I’ve enjoyed both Coffees from this region I’ve had and am actively on the lookout for more!

Bright and fruity up top but with a really solid toffee/cacao powder base

A bit of a funky natural. Seems kinda muddled and over fermented. But cranberry sauce and earthy chocolate come through. Seems to have picked up a bit of a spearmint or some sort of herbal note as the weeks have gone on

Really awesome juice bomb. Lots of hops and grapefruit up front with a nice nut and berry finish.

Enjoyed at the SSOB!

Delicious, fruity, a little tea like. I could definitely see myself drinking this as a daily driver!

Enjoyed at the SSBO!

Pungent before grind and during extraction, which is quite interesting, meat/savoury like.
Tried with chemex.
Body is balanced and the flavours linger for a while. Aromas are complex but not off putting. Am I crazy to think soy sauce?

I tried this coffee as an AeroPress at Dispatch’s St-Laurent location and it was fantastic. Probably one of the nicest AeroPress coffees I’ve ever tried. It started out with nice stone fruit flavours, and finished up with a delicious syrupy finish. The body was perfect, not too heavy
This coffee had many signature Kenyan notes. It was nice at room temperature, and would be a good coffee for anyone looking for typical Kenyan-tasting coffee!

One of the best and most unique coffees I’ve ever tried! Chinese specialty coffee seems to be more than just a novelty, it’s proving to be great coffee. This coffee (which I brewed as a V60) had a nice medium-light body, with really unique nutty and grape flavours. The lingering aftertaste was very pleasant. Overall, I couldn’t be happier with this coffee!
This cup had a nice, rich and soothing feel to it. The flavours were subtle, and not too overpowering. A nice morning cup!
Sweet coffee that felt really fruity and juice- like. I could drink this everyday.
This coffee is perfumey/ floral. Litterally flowers with dark chocolate notes. Then gives you berries and grapefruit notes. Nice after taste and nice coffee.
Tastes like sucking on a tart berry. Made as an espresso. Nice fruity flavour. Good natural Ethiopian.
Du fruit, du fruit, du fruit. Un aspect un peu floral, tout en douceur. Fin chocolaté. Olfaction un peu terreuse, très bon café.

I brewed this as a V60 and as a Kalita 185. Both times I got similar taste notes, with a sweet apple-like snappiness to it. The roast did taste a little bit grassy, but overall was a pleasant cup nonetheless.

This is a great medium espresso, and is versatile as it comes out nice as a straight shot or with milk. It is a great option for cafes who don’t wish to have two separate hoppers for straight/milk-based drinks
Tea like and full of Meyer lemon and honey. Bright and juicy and super clean. I think of this coffee often

My first coffee from one of Ontario’s newest roasters and it’s a great first release. I haven’t had many good Mexicans, but this one was great. It pulled a really nice, big bodied shot for cortados. I also took notice of the very consistent roast profile - well done!

Solid filter with a pretty clean finish. The acidity is present but not over powering and drinks like an English breakfast tea.

I’ve had better results pulling shots on my espresso machine and found it pops a lot more when made as a straight double shot or in an americano. The acidity and body work well without being too intense to drink without milk. It can work as a milk drink but it definitely gets overshadowed when cut with frothed milk.
