Delicious, well balanced and great berry like acidity. Not a tomato bomb by any means! Has a black tea finish with a relatively juicy mouthfeel.

As this cools you get a nice Chocolate covered orange flavour that turns into a bergamot linger. When freshly brewed there’s a lot of bell pepper and tomato. Let this one sit! It’ll open up into something delicious.

A wonderful Colombian coffee that shows off what care and attention at origin can produce. A very nice acidity that trails off into a milk chocolate finish. The peach acidity presents itself more as it cools.

Enjoyed on a V60, brewed at 1:17 (16g : 280ml), 96c and 3:00 draw down.
Enjoyed as a batch brew at Cafe Neve. A nice dark chocolate and fruit sweetness. A relatively light body with a pretty short finish. A solid filter option.
Beautifully clean coffee. Earthy sweetness with a bright pop of berry.
Absolutely wonderful. It tastes like a summery IPA: grapefruit, hops, a little bitter finish with a mild sweetness. Excited to keep sipping on this.

The dry coffee came out the gate with some serious hoppy notes. Once I started the brew, rose fragrance overpowered my senses.

The cup is clean, and subtle, with almost a grapefruit bitterness. 

Brewed both as a Kalita 185 and V60
From the moment we cracked it open, I immediately fell in love. Strong grapefruit hops on the nose, short finish but crazy flavour.

Really great as a single origin espresso, especially
over ice! A nice punch with a clean, fruity acidity and finish.
One of the best Kenya’s I’ve had in a long time.

A light bodied and tea-like experience which is really surprising for a natural! Not even remotely close to over fermentation, offering up a subtle rose like flavour. Not my usual preference but still delicious none the less.
Review in progress*

Very fruit forward when brewed at a 1:15 ratio. A nice kiwi acidity with a red apple flavour. Some black tea-like linger with a sprinkle of brown sugar.

Would highly recommend!
Definitely my favorite in comparison with the natural. Really enjoyable cuppa!

If you’re looking for a slightly more developed roast  this one makes a fantastic every day espresso. With classic heavy notes of caramel, date and bakers chocolate it pairs best in milk-based espresso drinks.
With notes of peanut butter & raspberry jam this Brazilian Natural evokes memories of eating PB&J sandwiches as a kid. I found this most delightful as a pour-over with my Kalita Wave.

For those who prefer a more developed roast yet want to venture into more unique coffee offerings this would be a great place to start. This coffee brought heavy notes reminiscent of a Black Forest Cake. With sweet cherry and rich chocolate.
Another beauty from Lüna! Sweet and full of baking spices and dried fruits

Took a couple tries to get a brew I liked. I set the grind a little bit coarser than usual, and did a 15.5:1 ratio and it turned out quite nice. Heavy body. Fragrant nose almost like caramelized roses. Medium sweetness and acidity and a long finish. Tastes kind of earthy, almost savoury, with dark cherry and muted jasmine.
Sweet and bright with a delicate body
Très bon pour un petit Latte. Juste un soupçon de lait afin de ne pas trop masquer  le très bon, subtil et complexe goût du café

This has been such a treat when brewed as an americano! Very sweet with a light but complex acidity. I wish for a bit more brightness to balance out the chocolate/fruit notes a bit more. Maybe tweaking my brew a bit could yield that result!
Even in espresso, strawberry was very present. Sweet one
Lüna seems to do no wrong, and this coffee is a perfect example of that. To execute a roast that eventuates a fruity characteristic while somehow accomplishing a malt milkshake body is impressive.
This coffee is wild. The tart raspberry that’s immediately balanced by milk chocolate is almost addicting. Perfect dessert coffee!
Pretty solid as a single origin espresso! I found it a little vegetal on the finish but overall pretty fruit forward with a nice dark chocolate mid palate.
Really solid as a filter and comes out pretty well as an espresso over ice. Plays decently with milk but would definitely recommend it more without.
Absolutely fantastic as a cold brew. Loads of fruitiness on the front that trails off into a delicious milk chocolate finish. Well balanced.
Grosse présence de fruits rouges, solide. MOK - Bruxelles
Round and we'll balanced. Very good morning drip.
I LOVED this coffee, & I am typically not a fruity/berry coffee person. The beans smell like fruit pie! It was fantastic! I went to buy several bags but they were out, sadly. Next time!
Regular espresso blend. Came out really nice in lattes. Nothing exceptional though, in my opinion.

I’m normally not a fan of Colombian coffees. I find the richer notes tend to overpower the acidity. This was not at all the case here. Such a balanced and clean cup. Very bright but still fades away into a wonderfully rich and chocolate filled linger.

The best Colombian coffee I’ve had in a long while. 🤤

Recipe:

Ratio: 16:272 (1:17)
Temp: 96c
Time: 3:15
Grind size: 14 Baratza Encore
Dripper: Mountain Dripper (155 filters)
Routine:
- 60ml bloom for 30s
- @ 30s pour ~110ml
- @ 1:15 pour ~102ml
Made this coffee today with the Kalita wave 185, and it came out nicely. The coffee has a nice body, started with milky chocolate notes, and had a light fruity aftertaste

If you like more “classic” flavours—chocolates, nuts, etc.—this coffee is for you! Considering it’s a naturally processed coffee, I was expecting it to be more fruit forward. I found it a little too muted for my tastes. I would’ve liked to see more acidity. There’s an extremely faint hint of pineapple, which I would’ve liked to see more pronounced. It leans much more towards coconut because of the development.

I brewed this in a Mountain Dripper at 96c with a brew time of 3:00 @ 1:16.

This cup is as magnificent as it sounds. Beautiful stone fruit on the front end with an almost fresh baked croissant buttery-ness on the back end that just intensified as the cup cooled. Clean, sweet, complex and lingering in the best way possible. I fell in love instantly.
This is easily one of the most magnificent fruit explosions I’ve ever had the pleasure of brewing. Completely in love.
Super café, le bleuet est tellement bien exploité, du solide !

Loving this lot oh so much. Brewed it as an Aeropress and it came out with that nice, silky black tea flavour with beautiful fruity notes interweaved between. The finish is wonderfully milk chocolatey with a dash of brown sugar. Really happy to have this coffee as my travel companion 🤤
An amazing coffee and unusually clean natural. Floral notes with bright strawberry and mango acidity.
Roasted too dark for me
An amazing berry bomb
A great coffee with strong lime flavor and florals, nice complexity
I thought this one may have been under developed. Nice acidity when hot but as it cools down it’s a bit vegetal
Berry bomb

Edit: I have to update this as it was one of the top 3 for me during a cupping of 10 coffees. Incredibly delicate, floral, sweet and still acidic enough to be vibrant. A huge black tea + bergamot flavour with some peach acidity. Fades almost to a jasmine. Excellent, excellent, excellent!

Beautiful as a single origin espresso! Was lucky enough to enjoy this at the Discovery HQ. Really wonderful fruit notes that end on a spicy note. Very much like fuzzy peach! Highly recommended. 🤤

Enjoyed it in a cappuccino at the Discovery HQ in Victoria. Good base for milk drinks. Well balanced and just the right amount of light acidity to play with the milk. Very chocolate forwards. A great classic profile.

Pourover prep from Boxcar Harbourfront. Very light bodied and curbed acidity, the strawberry is like you'd get from a fruit-steeped water (like cucumber water but with strawberry. at the same time the sweetness isn't exactly natural-like (in a good way, not heavy handed). Very aqueous and drinkable to room temp. Would probably be sick as a flash chilled pour over

Had this coffee on espresso as an allongé at Pista's cafe in Montreal. Wasn't a coffee with a particularly great balance, tasting quite citric in its acidity. However, diluting it with a bit of hot water in an allongé turned that down a bit and brought out notes of lime, grape juice, and a mouthfeel reassembling that of melted butter. However these notes were quite subtle.  All in all made for a nice allongé, and got better as it cooled down, with notes of cantaloupe coming through.
Incroyable, on aurait cru un blend Chine-Kenya. Popcorn est là, finale fruit rouge, terreux et riche

Holy shit. The aromas coming from this freshly brewed were intoxicating. Light, fruity and tea-like. The taste was a wonderful journey from apple skins and orange to black tea with a milk chocolate finish. I’m super impressed with just how much this coffee pops. 😍

Enjoyed on a Seraphim + V60 combo @ Revolver in downtown Vancouver.

Fairly complex and very fruit forward. Not as delicate as I normally like but still solid. A high berry note on the front palate that transitions to a nice black tea-like note on the mid and ends with a bittersweet chocolate and brown sugar finish.

Enjoyed as a pour over at Nemesis in downtown Vancouver.
Interesting coffee, probably one of the better naturals I've had in a while.  Still has that odd winey natural process flavour going on though.
Fruit bomb

Really enjoyed this as a pour over but even more so as a cold brew! In a pour over the delicate tea like flavours are more present but when brewed cold, the berry-like flavours pop and meld more with the tea-like qualities. Both yield a nice chocolate and brown sugar flavour with a peach like fuzziness!
Very refreshing and tea like. The coffee is very strawberry forward.

I have tried this coffee a number of different preps and I'm sadly disappointed at the roast level here. Evident right out of the bag, it's quite roasty, even on espresso.

Had high hopes, branding is great, and their reputation had my expectations much higher.

Made as both a pour over in the Mountain Dripper and as a S/O espresso shot.

This works equally well as both but I prefer it as an espresso! The citrus notes seem to be more pronounced before quickly shifting to a deeper, richer chocolate flavour. As a pour over, I found the chocolate to be the most pronounced.
Strong profile throughout cooling. Started off with fruit forward and shifted to a strong papaya after taste as it cooled. Highly recommended
This coffee came out great both as a V60 and Kalita 185. It was surprisingly sweet, and refreshing. Would definitely try to pull an espresso shot with this!

Fantastic as a single origin espresso! Quite a bit of an acid bomb, so if that’s not your thing, beware. The mix of hoppy and herb like flavours and the high citrus acid are a wonderful combo.

Enjoyed at the newly opened cafe Éclaire on Maguire.
Very clean coffee
First time EVER experiencing a coffee from China. Truly an amazing coffee.
Best espresso coffee in Montreal

I thought this coffee was very balanced and not over acidic. I really enjoyed the cooler the coffee got the more passion fruit was tasted. The dry milk taste was a bit weird, but fit this coffee well.
One of the best Ethiopian coffees of 2019. It is my favourite roast of the year so far. Adventurous.
Ethiopian coffees are my favourite and this was one of the best of early 2019. Drinking it was a little like biting into a blueberry muffin.

batch 10. when hot perfumery peach taste and aroma, along with some apricot notes, then natural coffee taste, strawberry gummy acidity, nice light tea finish. I got some more coffee from my friend. 29 day off roast, the cup I had today had a longer finish, else from the tea, noticing bit herbal jelly notes.(1:13.3, medium grind). Fairly easy to extract, coarser the grind works better for the coffee, higher water to coffee ratio. 1:17 (tim uses in this tasting with subscriber YouTube video)

Ah, the coffee that made me realize the water at my new apartment sucked!

I couldn’t dial this coffee in no matter how hard I tried. I went from 1:15 to 1:18 to really bring out all the delicate notes I could and it just tasted flat and bland. Having had other coffee from Quietly I was determined to make it work almost positive it wasn’t the green or the roast.

Finally I brought it to the Montreal Coffee Academy for a small cupping and there it was, staring me in the face. Complex, sparking and tea-like. All the flavours promised on the bag came through. As the coffee cooled the pink lemonade exploded out after being very berry forward.

One of the cleanest natural Ethiopians I’ve had in a while!

Now to fix my water situation 👀
Generally not a natural fan but this is pretty decent.
Creamy and super smooth. Body feels thick but the flavour profile is quite delicate. Earl Grey, a bit of grass/herbal notes, quite bite of acid, medium fruit sweetness.
Hadn’t had a natural Kenyan before. Very pleasant and enjoyable- not the usual flavors you get out of naturals. Much more nuanced flavors and clean.
Great Kenya, very solid. Enough development to not have anything resembling tomato, not baked either. Snappy and fun.
I am not surprised at how much I enjoyed this coffee, superbly clean and balanced natural. Very thankful to have a regular customer drop some of this off for us to try.
Always love TW’s Finca Temana offerings. I’ve had it for several harvests now- it is always one of the easiest drinking bright coffees. deep, plenty of intrigue. Great coffee.

Finally got to visit Sump Nashville- and enjoyed a pour-steady prepared Ethiopia Nano Challa. Really big washed Ethiopia! Very tactile, citrus really does border on olio-saccharin rind, great florals. Was served a high brew strength pour over, which may have exaggerated my perception of the body level- but it sure was there!
Sweet and juicy

This coffee was nice! Tried this coffee as a Chemex and it came out very clean, with a bright, crisp finish. The berry notes overpowered the slight tomato taste that I found lingered a bit. Overall a good cup!

Absolutely excellent. If you’re looking for a sweet, fun, acidic coffee, you found it! For some it might border on tomato but I got hit with all strawberry and lime.

Enjoyed as a V60 and was a standout at a cupping.

This was an odd experience. It was great as a cold brew! Very delicate and sweet. Maple syrup and a bit of bergamot mostly. Would recommend for that!

However. This coffee did not fair as well in a cupping and as a pour over. It tasted fairly flat and cardboard-y. Which is surprising that it did so well as a cold brew!

Very tea-like! Super easy drinking experience and pretty clean. I find the transition at the tail end to dark chocolate a little sudden and intense but as the coffee cools it becomes more complementary.

Enjoyed as a V60 and in a cupping!

Had this coffee at a cupping. Next to the Kercha from Discovery, this unfortunately didn’t hold a candle. It’s still a solid coffee but definitely more of a muted flavour. I re-brewed as a V60 and it showed a bit more promise. I did find a strong bell pepper flavour in the cupping vs. brewing on the V60, which had more of the pleasant chocolate notes.
Very special one

Loved this coffee! I found it was comforting and had a nice palatable bitterness to it, something like orange zest, with a nice acidity. The citrus notes are present from start to finish, and strengthen as the drink cools. It would be interesting to see how this works as an iced coffee!
I love dark roasts that are not burnt or oily, Gotham is incredible, packs a mountain of flavor without any burnt taste.

This coffee hits with a sharp acidity, juicy mouthfeel and strong floral and honey linger that shifts to a chocolate. I’ve experimented with a few recipes and I’ve found that 1:16 at 3:00 seems to give the best results so far. Brewed in a V60 at 94c
One of the best if not the best coffee I’ve tried so far. Incredibles aromas in the cup! Thanks nomad for that
I love Tres Fincas! It was my first pour over coffee and I will keep on having this as my go-to cup!
Very special
Really fruity. Comes great in Chemex and espresso. Punchy enough for lattes and cappuccinos.
An amazing, fruity, well balanced coffee. One of the best
Fresh fresh melon
Refreshing coffee

Wonderfully balanced cup! 

Brewed on a moccamaster 45g/760ml
Good coffee

One of my favourite South American coffees to date. I love a coffee that harmonizes acidity and richer, earthier notes. I think Kaito nailed it with this one. It packs such a nice punch of red berry and bergamot at the front and smoothly transitions to a bitter sweet chocolate finish with a hint of brown sugar.

I’ve been really, really enjoying this as a double shot of espresso. Doing 17.5g in and 42g out @ ~30s on my Breville Barista Express. The complexity really shines I find.

In a V60 over you get a really buttery mouth feel and the acidity blends very cleanly with the chocolate notes, almost perfectly. There’s a bit of a buttered popcorn vibe to it as it cools, which I quite enjoyed. It’s still vibrant but if you’re looking for something a bit more in your face, highly recommended as an espresso shot.
Complex sweet coffee that resembles strawberry jam with the hint of vanilla and dried cherries.
One of the sweetest, most unbelievably juicy coffees I’ve ever cupped! It was Turkish delight and juicy berries and dark chocolate all at once.

Wow; any person that wants to enjoy; feel and taste what a Specialty Coffee should taste like must try this.

Show starts from the aroma once the bag is opened; definitely a show stopper!!
Solid Brazilian, comforting and exactly what you expect it to be
Bright and spicy coffee!
Nice natural processed Kenya that seemed a bit too dirty for my taste.
Bright and sweet lime/red currant Kenya!
Very like
Good coffee
Solid comforting coffe, tastes like an old fashioned apple pie

A solid all arounder from Luna. I struggled with the greenish vegetal note in cupping, but dialing in brew or two, it really struck me as "hoppy", in the way it combines greenness with florality, citrus notes and balanced acidity and bitterness.
well balance, sweet, nice fruit acidité
Very high in sweetness with pleasant acidity and more body than I would have expected. No bitterness whatsoever.
First pour over so far, Kalita 155 13.5 -> 201 at 2:45 and pretty much what it says on the tin. Can't wait for espresso
Soooooo goood !
This coffee is in our top 5 from Sqiare Mile!
Made it with Yama tower. Very fruity first taste which turned chocolatey quickly. Next time I’d adjust to get more of the fruit.

A little darker than I’m looking for typically, especially for filter. Very little brightness in the cup, mostly on the classic side with a tail end of toast as a pour over. However, as a flat white, the richer, chocolaty notes play nicely with the milk.

Would recommend if you’re looking for a classic profile in a single origin.
An amazing, well balanced coffee. Really great in espresso. No so light roast, but enough to savour all the flavours.
V60 at Phin. Very enjoyable, sweet and delicate washed.

Has a nice punch to it. Definitely more on the developed side but still offers some brightness. Ends on a chocolate and brown sugar note.

Enjoyed at Odessa in Montreal.

This coffee was extremely complex. Each sip there was something new to explore. Lots of sweetness with a crisp, clean acidity bordering on effervescent. Body was tea-like. Sweetness reminded me of simple syrup with notes of stone fruit, citrus, & gentle florals.
Quite a nice medley of different flavours! Very floral but still has a nice chocolate finish. Enjoyed on batch brew @ Cafe DAX in Montreal.

What appears to have been a bypass variation V60 at show & tell. Very much as advertised (the packaging has different tasting notes than noted here). Very nice berry note with traditional Colombian character
Amazing anaerobic coffee. Loads of strawberry jam and cinnamon. Really great on V60.

This makes for an excellent first thing in the morning cup. Loads of comforting marshmallow and bittersweet chocolate while it’s still warm. As it cools it gets a little herby and moves towards a black-tea like flavour and mouthfeel, while still keeping the roundness of the marshmallow. The bittersweet chocolate takes on an almost brown sugar like feel when it cools.

Enjoyed as a V60 @ Cafe Lali.
Truly lives up to the name. Blended it with nicely textured milk and had it tasting like Haagen Dazs coffee ice cream.

Loved this coffee in espresso! A really well balanced cup with the right amount of acidity and deeper, richer notes. If you’re looking for something easy with a bit of pop, this’ll be a great purchase.

A nice solid Colombian offering. Very much a heavy maple syrup note with a lovely tamarind and dark chocolate backing. As it cooled the black tea-like qualities became more apparent.

Enjoyed as a V60: 1:16 (20g:320ml), total time 3:15, temp 100c using James Hoffman’s V60 recipe.
One of my favorite consistent coffees to use for espresso!
Very delicate and floral

A nice, explosive Kenyan coffee! Considering it’s a dry processed coffee it’s very clean. A great tea-like quality to it on the mouth feel and tail end alongside a molasses like note. 

Brewed in a V60 @ 1:16 (28g : 448ml), 4:15 total brew at 100c. Brewed using James Hoffman’s recipe.
Beautiful coffee! You'll taste exactly what they are promising on the packaging. Eucaliptus, rosemary and sweet mint. Rare coffee, super satisfying, beautiful.
So good. One of my favorites across many roasters. Grape soda. Sweet. Seemed a bit effervescent. Sad to see the last cup go.

Such a wonderful, juicy mouthfeel with a very herbal / tea-like flavour to it. Awesome combination. Very well balanced.

Brewed as a V60, 1:16 (18g : 288ml), 2:50 total time, 100c water, brewed using James Hoffman’s recipe.

Very acidic and fruity on the espresso side. 
Drip was a lot more balanced and earthy. Smell is homey, if baked chocolate pastries.

The aroma on this coffee immediately made me think of fruity pebbles cereal! The second the water hit the dry coffee bed, I got a whiff of that sweet, sugary goodness.

The flavour is very much inline with the aroma, though it turns into a fermented fruity pebble. Definitely a mix of wine and dried fruit, with a tail end of almond/marzipan and darker chocolate.

I’m kind of surprised at how toned town the acidity is considering it’s a carbonic process. Well balanced and fairly intricate. 🙌

Brewed on a V60 using James Hoffman’s recipe.

1:16 (20g : 320ml), 2:50 brew time, 100c water.

Even though this is the white, there is plenty of development to this coffee. Struggled a bit with over extraction, but this drinks really well in a stronger brew ratio. Very sweet and sugary, med-low acidity but very nice fruity character when cooler. Roast is probably appropriate for spro, will prepare one.

This coffee was nice and surprisingly clean for a natural. It had a general fruitiness that I enjoyed, but I couldn’t pinpoint any particular flavour notes (might have boiled the water too hot). It had a bit of a light tea-like note which I also enjoyed.
Came out better in chemex or v60 than espresso. Very very nice though
A bit classic for my taste, but still very coffee there.
The best from 49th in my opinion. Great in pour overs (chemex or v60) and also in espresso. Strong enough to cut trough milk base coffees.
A bit too classic for my taste, but still a very decent cup.
Delicate describes this coffee very well. At least in V60. The beans were older and yet still good.

This coffee has a lot of really nice desirable flavours. I really liked the acidity, it was nice and snappy. There were still some vegetal notes, but they were not very overpowering. Overall it was still a nice coffee!
Excellent gesha, naturally processed and unique notes as it cools
This is so much pistachio and oats is crazy, (2 taste notes that need to be added to the list)
Truly unique experience to trying this Chinese Yunnan offering at Rabbithole. This coffee is so sweet and perfect for an espresso!
This coffee was deliciously juicy! It tasted like a juicy, rich raspberry tea. I brewed it as a kalita wave, and can’t wait to try it again over ice!
A pure explosion of Jasmine!
Full body, balanced by light notes of nutmeg. Good in espresso, better as an Americano, but my favorite is on the V60

A solid Nicaraguan offering with an awesome tealike quality. Subtle acidity with a nice tail of dark chocolate as it finishes. Definitely holds up well when cooled.

Brewed in a V60 using the Hoffman recipe. 16g : 280ml (1:17.5), 60ml bloom for 45s, total draw time 3:05.
Absolutely fantastic as an espresso. Well balanced, fruit forward and ends with a lovely black tea finish. Made by Yadi @ Fika Cafe in Toronto.

Definitely on the chocolately side of things. A more classic profile with a lot more sweetness. Would be a great introductory coffee.

Enjoyed at SAN Coffee Room in Toronto.

Interesting marshmallow forward that turns into salted caramel with a dark chocolate finish. A nice approachable Rwandan coffee.

Enjoyed on bar at the SAN coffee room in Toronto.
Blown away by this China coffee! Black tea notes alongside juicy berry fruits. Aftertaste let it down a little but an amazing coffee nonetheless.

Fantastic as a single origin espresso. Wonderful cinnamon and fruit flavours. Very well balanced.

Enjoyed at Brodflour in Toronto.

The dry aromatics of this coffee were loaded with fruity pebbles and a hint of brown sugar. When brewed, the coffee is fruit forward as it cools and spice forward when hot. A nice tea like body with a relatively short finish. 

Brewed on a V60 using the Hoffman recipe.

Time: 2:50
Grind size: 17 on an Encore
Temp: 98c
Bloom: 60ml for 45s
Ratio: 1:17 (16.5g : 288ml)
Excellent espresso blend ! A bit too light for lattes but coming out perfectly in cappuccino.
I’ve ordered this for the office a few times and it’s the only coffee that has had people commenting on it. Mostly served as an espresso, its a big favourite in the office.
I like this as a cold brew. It’s had mixed reactions in the office as espresso. I prefer it as cold brew
Maybe my second favourite coffee. Tried it first as a pour over and it was incredible. I’ve had it as espresso since and it’s really good but not as good as the pour over.

Great Ethiopian coffee from the newly established Monkland! This is a sign of good things to come. Well balanced, nice and fruity without too much acidity and a wonderful tea like quality. Exactly what you’d expect from a washed Ethiopian Sidama.

Enjoyed as an Espresso at Monkland’s launch at Cafe Elementaire in NDG.

Well balanced and a nice all-around single origin espresso. A safe bet if you’re looking for something that walks the line of approachable yet punchy!
Coffee from nomad never fail me. This coffee is sweet with balance of acidity. The body is medium-low which brings me brightness. Hint of violet flowers also gives a very good scent.
Underdevelopment

I’m positive that this is one of the best coffees I’ve ever had, and I’m having a hard time remembering one that I’ve enjoyed more. Maybe it’s the story behind it, maybe it’s the scarce quantity, or maybe it’s just that good. 

So juicy, so sweet, so damn good.

This coffee was unfortunately underwhelming. I couldn’t get great results from any pour over method, and the best cups I got were on the Aeropress. Lacking the sweetness I’d expect from both the roaster and the origin.

I appreciate Propeller joining the collaboration to purchase this coffee, but it’s a little too developed to appreciate everything these farmers have to offer. Unfortunately that’s been the case with most Propeller coffees I’ve tried.
One of Toronto’s best does it again. This is a classic yet clean natural Ethiopian. I’ll miss this bag when it’s gone.

One of the cleanest naturals I can recall, and an unconventional approach to natural Ethiopians. This coffee exchanges the classic blueberries for raspberries, and it’s the perfect balance of sweetness and acidity (just like real raspberries are!)

A solid Guatemalan coffee with a nice balance of citrus and richer, chocolate notes. 

Enjoyed as a V60
Definitely not a bad coffee, just not a great one. I've enjoyed it although I can't say I'll remember it. Very light bodied with mild sweetness and raspberry like acidify. Finish doesn't really go on
Nice Kenian, but I wouldn't go with the recipe La Cabra is suggesting for V60, with the ratio of 1:14. This coffee tastes better with 1:17

This is such an incredibly balanced coffee. I had some trouble dialing it in at first but finally settled on a tighter than normal ratio for me @ 1:15. It really brought out the full impact and nuance of the cup. Still very tea like in mouthfeel without sacrificing a juicy texture. 

Brewed in a V60, 16g : 240ml, 2:45min, Hoffman recipe

Another knockout from Hatch! Well developed, punchy and balanced. A great mix of tea-like qualities in flavour and a heavier body. 

Brewed in a V60 at 1:17 (16g : 272ml), brew time 3:00, 100c water using the Hoffman recipe.

A nicely balanced washed Ethiopian! Lovely clean, faint tamarind/bergamot like acidity that trails off into a black tea and ends with almond and chocolate.

Brewed in a V60, 1:16 (16g : 256ml), 3:15m, 100c using the Hoffman recipe.
Underdevelopment
This natural was pretty clean, and overall very pleasant brewed as a v60. I liked that it wasn’t muddy, and had a nice rich sweetness.
Not what you’d expect from a natural Gesha at all. Very clean and earthy with a nice Tobacco flavour and bittersweet chocolate.

A clean washed Gesha that’s heavily on the classic side! Something that you don’t typically associate with Gesha’s. A hint of acidity very reminiscent of dried fruits and black tea with a nice dark chocolate finish.
Good tasting coffee with milk chocolate sweetness, cherry/raspberry-like acidity and hints of bakers choc. Syrupy and not an overpowering fermentation taste, which may or may not be your thing.

Incredibly clean, complex and just a joy to drink. 

Wonderful berry acidity that turns into a lemon grass and anise herb-y-ness and ends with a honey sweetness.

I want this coffee while sitting in a ray of sunlight on a chill fall morning while listening to the sounds of the city waking up.

Brew method: V60, 1:16 (23g : 368ml), 3:05m, 100c, Hoffman Recipe

Really interesting coffee! Lots of cherry sweetness, some fermentation but not as intense as a natural coffee. Finishes on a dark chocolate, semi bitter note. I feel like this would be very nice as an iced coffee.
This is so up my alley. Like a fresh raspberry tea with a nice citrus and black tea that ends in caramel and milk chocolate.
Very clean and elegant coffee
Balanced cup with a surprisingly strong body. Acidity is present but not very forward like many other Kenya's. Strong notes of cola and black cherry with wine undertones.
Solid sweet round ❤️
Very well balanced coffee with crazy fruity and acidic notes, I brewed it with the V60 but also super sweet and nice adicity for espresso, very light roast
Very bright for being a natural. I got super high extraction for both espresso and V60. Highly recomended. Very fine acidity and fruity notes
Very clean, bright and sweet. Tea like body. Enjoyed a sample at the ECCM.

Tried this as pour over at ECCM 19
Chocolatey and smooth
Had this as pourover at ECCM 19. It was the anerobic processed version of this which was different. Cinnamon notes were subtle.
A nicely layered Ethiopian with wonderful tea like qualities.

Surprisingly big gesha beans. I brewed 14.6/238gr in 4’, a bit coarser would have given a better extraction, however really delicate and bright, could taste all the apricot, pineapple and orange cup notes for long time
By now made it as espresso and could get really high extraction with very well balanced acidity-sweetness. Could taste the fruity and nutty cup notes with a pleasant after taste

This opens up into a beautiful, floral, sweet and clean cup as it cools. A great Ethiopian coffee from a wonderful region 👌

Brewed using the Hoffman recipe. 1:17 (16g : 272ml), 3:45m, 100c
One of my favorites from AZs best!
A nice tea-like Kenyan coffee with a slight punch of fruit on the front palate. Ends with bitter sweet chocolate and graham cracker.

Best filter cup I have ever had. I used the 4:6 recipe v60, very coarse grind and used 4 pours of 45gr for the 60%, 3’30”. 1.35% tds 18% extraction. I will grind finner next time for checking, but the cup is super clean with very blackcurrant and orange taste and super amazing after taste.
Ne

Incredibly clean, well balanced and not overly acidic. A lovely sugar sprinkled dried fruit on the front that ends with a hint hibiscus and black tea.

Brewed on the V60 using the Hoffman recipe.

Ratio: 1:16 (25g : 400ml)
Time: 3:50
Temp: 100c

The development is pushed a little too far for my taste. However as the base to a cappuccino it works quite well! The chocolate flavours pair nicely and the slight acidity emphasizes the little that’s in steamed milk,

If you’re looking for something a little more classic with a dash of acidity, this is a good starting point!

Had this at Black fox in NYC on espresso, the shot I had was well balanced, super sweet, and had one of the nicest aftertaste I've seen. Definitely want to have more square mile after that! This was my first time.

A nice balanced, clean and tea-like natural Ethiopian!

Enjoyed as batch brew filter @ September Cafe in Montreal.

Wow. Blown away by this one. It reminds me of a cherry cordial with a sprinkle of nutmeg on a foundation of oolong tea. I’m not even sure that makes sense but I think that’s because this coffee doesn’t make sense.

If you’re looking for something with a unique balance of textures and flavours this is it.

Brewed on a V60 with the Hoffman recipe: 1:16 (16g : 256ml), 100c, 2:50m

This coffee is very versatile, and comes out nice as a shot of espresso, or as a filter brew. It’s balanced, and has a low acidity and nice body. I’m a big fan of rich coffees, and this one is right in my wheelhouse. Could do with a tad more sweetness, but that might just be my brews!
İ love barn🖤

Really liked this Coffee. Great und silky
 texture.

A nice stone fruit acidity and black tea flavour that ends with a caramel and dark chocolate finish. The mouth feel is that if a milky black tea.

Method: Aeropress (not inverted)
Ratio: 1:10 (20g : 200ml) diluted to 1:18
Temp: 98c
Grind: 10 on my encore
Routine:
- Fill cup with difference of water (160ml)
- Place Aeropress on top of receptacle and fill with grounds
- Pour 200ml and stir constantly until 45s passed
- Place plunger into Aeropress and pull back to create minor suction
- at 1:15 start plunging until you hear the first hiss (should be finished around 2:00)

I’ll be honest, if you’re looking for a familiar profile this is not your coffee. It’s not fruity and sugary sweet, and it’s not rich with hazelnut and chocolate. It bucks all of those trends in a beautiful way. The savory notes were woodsy and cathartic, and the mint flavors for me were like spearmint. The sweetness was like eating raw sugar cane, it just coats your mouth. I have pined for this coffee (pun intended) since I finished the bag, and it is certainly my most memorable of 2020. I went for a shorter ratio than normal as these flavors can handle all the body you can give them.
